b"Are you patient?
Are you caring?
Are you flexible?

You could be a respite care volunteer! If you\xe2\x80\x99re looking for a way to help out in your community, and would prefer to donate your time instead of your money, then volunteering as a respite caregiver is a great way to help someone in need \xe2\x80\x94 while also filling your life with a sense of purpose and philanthropy. 

What is a respite care volunteer? As a respite care volunteer, your main purpose would be to ensure the care receiver is comfortable while their primary caregiver is away. You won\xe2\x80\x99t be responsible for bathing, dressing, dispensing medication or cooking (though you may need to ensure they\xe2\x80\x99re eating and drinking). You can also offer minor assistance for things like walking them to the restroom, but for the most part it\xe2\x80\x99s about keeping them company.

It's an incredibly rewarding activity. Just ask Debbie Tahany, a testing engineer specialist at American Family who volunteers as a respite caregiver. Her advice? \xe2\x80\x9cDo it. I don\xe2\x80\x99t think you\xe2\x80\x99ll regret it. Take a chance. And as a volunteer, you\xe2\x80\x99re not committing for life. More people would be good at it than you think.\xe2\x80\x9d

If you\xe2\x80\x99re interested in volunteering as a respite caregiver, reach out to a volunteer coordinator at a parish or church, community resource program and nursing homes or hospitals in your area. However big or small, you can leave a lasting impact on someone\xe2\x80\x99s life for the better. All it takes is making the first step."

b'When American Family employee Elliot Franklin started digging into his family\xe2\x80\x99s past, he learned that his ancestors were an integral part of the American experience: Free people. In the 1840s, Elliot\xe2\x80\x99s ancestors, the Weavers, left North Carolina to flee the Fugitive Slave Act and settled in Indiana where they built a thriving, free, pre-Civil War farm community \xe2\x80\x94 suitably named Weaver. The town, which was part of the Underground Railroad, was built to produce wealth and provide a destination for those on the road to freedom. \nSince 1919, Elliot\xe2\x80\x99s family has returned to Weaver every year for a family reunion, with 2019 marking the centennial reunion. \xe2\x80\x9cHistory can feel distant, like on the pages of textbooks. But now, it has a pulse because I know my family helped shape early American history for the benefit of others,\xe2\x80\x9d says Elliot. \n#BlackHistoryMonth #DreamFearlessly #EmployeeShowcase #CompanyCulture'

b'September is Life Insurance Awareness Month. American Family Insurance employee Derek Kosmicki shares his firsthand experience with cancer and how his family, coworkers and agency owner helped him battle through, as did the knowledge he had life insurance. \xe2\x80\x9cWell, we found a cancer.\xe2\x80\x9d It was Feb. 25, 2019 when the doctor broke the news while I was still waking up from my colonoscopy sedation. There\xe2\x80\x99s probably no good way to tell someone they have cancer, so you might as well open with it.

In the coming weeks, I had surgery to remove a third of my colon, 39 lymph nodes (two that were cancerous) and a portion of a kidney. After a week in the hospital and another month to recover from that (which left me with a 6-inch scar on my stomach and an enviable set of 2-pack abs), I began chemotherapy. Three months, six treatments, and countless side effects later, I successfully completed treatment.

I\xe2\x80\x99ve tried to keep a positive mindset through it all, with varying degrees of success. After all, I\xe2\x80\x99m 39 years old with three children under the age of eight \xe2\x80\x93 some tears and fears are surely expected. And, I don\xe2\x80\x99t know if/when this cancer may come back. Still, staying positive has helped me realize a few things.

I learned that fear and modesty are terrible reasons not to go to the doctor. 
I am incredibly fortunate. 
The amount of support I\xe2\x80\x99ve had from American Family, from my boss to everyone in Personal Lines Underwriting Operations, has been special. From the beginning, they\xe2\x80\x99ve made sure I didn\xe2\x80\x99t have to worry about work, and instead could focus on getting better. It\xe2\x80\x99s meant the world to me and I can\xe2\x80\x99t imagine ever working anywhere else because of it.

Life insurance matters.

Finally, I realized how truly blessed and lucky I am. It would\xe2\x80\x99ve been nice to have this epiphany without a cancer diagnoses, but better late than never. I really understand what Lou Gehrig meant in his famous speech. He was right.

I have cancer, but I\xe2\x80\x99m the luckiest person I know.
#EmployeeStory #Company Culture #CancerSucks #LifeInsuranceAwarenessMonth'

b'Music has always been a big part of Sarah Suardi\xe2\x80\x99s life. When she thinks back on her childhood, Sarah sees her grandmother sitting with her at an old piano, teaching her how to play the keys. \xe2\x80\x9cWhen I was little and people asked me what I wanted to be when I grew up, I would say a singer,\xe2\x80\x9d Sarah says. :microphone: 
After years of trying to be a composer for video game soundtracks without any luck, she found herself at a crossroads. That\xe2\x80\x99s when the phone rang. It was a former classmate, asking if she\xe2\x80\x99d like to join his band. \xe2\x80\x9cIt was like that saying, \xe2\x80\x98When one door closes another opens,\xe2\x80\x99\xe2\x80\x9d says Sarah. :musical_score: 
Sarah became the lead singer of AfterTime, a cinematic metal band based in Minneapolis, Minnesota. Their music combines the heavy drums and guitars of metal with elements of symphonic orchestral sounds \xe2\x80\x94 a subgenre of heavy metal music that is most popular in Europe.
:musical_notes:
